{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496929"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:59:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:59:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1439"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1439"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.04,0.15,0.07,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1439"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48328"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1439"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1439"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33246"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"242"},{"type":"tags","id":"2213"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6864"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7133"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12285"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48328"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a firm lump on her foot. The lump has gradually increased in size and is now rubbing on her shoes. She reports that the lump is smaller in the mornings but larger and more painful by the end of the day. She works in retail.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a firm, well-circumscribed lump on the dorsum of the right foot (Image). There is no loss of mobility of the ankle or toes, but she reports pain and discomfort under the lump when moving her foot. The lump is tender to palpation and transilluminates when a light is shone on it.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ganglion","Lipoma","Sebaceous cyst","Bunion","Fibroma"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is typical of a \u003Cstrong\u003Eganglion\u003C/strong\u003E cyst, which commonly occurs on the dorsum of the foot, wrist, or hand. Ganglion cysts arise from adjacent synovial joints or tendon sheaths and are filled with synovial fluid. Key features in this case include the gradual onset, fluctuation in size (smaller in the morning, larger at the end of the day), and transillumination. Ganglions are usually benign and may not require treatment unless they cause significant pain or functional impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elipoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign tumor composed of adipose tissue. While lipomas can occur on the foot, they typically present as soft, mobile masses that do not transilluminate. They also do not usually fluctuate in size throughout the day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esebaceous cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign cyst that forms from blocked sebaceous glands. These are more common on hair-bearing areas of the body and would not typically occur on the dorsum of the foot. Additionally, sebaceous cysts do not transilluminate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebunion\u003C/strong\u003E, or hallux valgus, is a bony deformity of the joint at the base of the big toe. It presents as a bony prominence on the side of the foot near the base of the big toe, not on the dorsum of the foot. Bunions also do not transilluminate or fluctuate in size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efibroma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign tumor composed of fibrous or connective tissue. While fibromas can occur in the foot (plantar fibroma), they typically present as firm, fixed masses that do not transilluminate or fluctuate in size. They are also more common on the plantar aspect of the foot rather than the dorsum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ganglion cysts commonly present as transilluminable swellings of the hand, wrist or dorsal foot."],"references":["Sakamoto A, Okamoto T, Matsuda S. Persistent Symptoms of Ganglion Cysts in the Dorsal Foot. Open Ortho J 2017; 11:1308-13"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33246"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1439"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17415"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17415"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c205fb30-5150-42b8-9f1c-fc6e339cb479.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c205fb30-5150-42b8-9f1c-fc6e339cb479.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":533}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33246"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-10T05:34:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-10T05:34:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1439"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48328"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"se